summary: Do you have any domestic Pokemon headcanons?
question: Do you have any domestic Pokemon headcanons?
answer:
In regards to Detective Pikachu? I actually do! They’re not really all that outlandish, but they’re kind of inspired by this fanfic idea I have bouncing around in my head.

It’s stated in the movie that Ryme City is known for not putting Pokémon against each other in combat, meaning that there’s no gym. It’s also stated in the intro video that Tim watches on the bullet train, that no trainers in Ryme City keep their Pokémon in PokéBalls.

Think about that for a second.

No PokéBalls.

The Pokémon aren’t caught in the wildlife setting their normally found in, they simply coexist in the city with the humans, like a shared habitat.

This could imply that the Pokémon are considered citizens of the city and have as much rights to live in the city as the humans do. And in that case it would make a lot of sense! Especially for Pokémon with more human-like genetic make up and instincts, like Machoke, Mr. Mime, Psychic and Ghost-types, higher evolved-bipedal Pokémon, etc. they can perform tasks that can be done by humans and benefit the economy, as per the very gritty, modern, capitalist setting Ryme City embodies.

But what about the Pokémon with more primal instincts, like Snorlax, who does nothing but eat and sleep? Or like Fire-types, who tend to be very easily combustible, or Flying-types who spend more of their time in the sky? Or the baby Pokémon! All of them have free reign of the city just as much as the humans. But where do they fit in as members of city life?

I think, that despite Howard’s self proclaimed salvation of Ryme City actually leaves a large portion of the Pokémon population trainer-less, and by extension, homeless.

Most of the Pokémon probably fair just fine this way and have adapted accordingly. Rather that trying to find food in their natural habitat, pokemon can beg for handouts from strangers and scour garbage cans, like squirrels, pigeons, stray dogs, etc. But there are other Pokémon who don’t find themselves so lucky, and night lash out and attack strangers if desperate enough. Which leads to a potential usefulness for the Pokémon division of the police department, to apprehend and potentially relocate dangerous Pokémon.

But on the other hand. This also opens the doors potentially to Pokémon adoption centers. Foster homes filled with dozens of homeless Pokémon. Pokémon trained to be service Pokémon, even cutesy Pokémon Cafes! Dozens of different ways to get a Pokémon partner, without using PokéBalls.

Seems like the perfect place for Harry to find a stray Pikachu, or for Tim to get a Pokémon partner without needing a PokéBall.

summary:
I think I didnt mention it here, but I really liked Detective Pikachu!
Its a fun movie, the characters are likable, and they did...
body:
I think I didnt mention it here, but I really liked Detective Pikachu!

Its a fun movie, the characters are likable, and they did an amazing job with the Pokemon and the setting. (I am thankful Mewtwo was SO faithfully done on his characterization)

If I had to say something bad, its that Detective Pikachu is a little bit too simple and straightforward on its plot. But nonetheless a great viewing for any Pokemon fan
